The day the devil spat on the blackberries. September 29th is one of the quarter days of the year in the Christian calendar. The quarter days were used by farmers to mark the changing of the seasons; as this was the time of harvest and preparation for the long winter ahead. The lore comes from the battle between the Archangel Michael and Lucifer. When Lucifer fell from grace and became Satan, he landed in a blackberry bush. He cursed, stomped and spat on the bush and berries. It is said that if you eat or pick blackberries after the feast of Michael, you will have bad luck or fall ill.

They are increasing in number over the last few years but, luckily for us, they are very easy to spot against the green foliage and within a few minutes they can be found and dispatched without use of chemicals. Margaret McCollum after the death of her husband Oswald Laurence, sits on the bench waiting to hear this recording that became one of London's most famous "Mind the gap" In 2003, Oswald died leaving a huge void in Margaret's heart. So Margaret found a way to feel his presence closest. After more than half a century, this voice was replaced by an electronic recording. Out of distress Margaret asked for this cassette tape from London transport company so she could continue listening to her husband's voice at home. After becoming aware of the moving history, the company decided to restore the announcement at the stop near where Margaret lives,at the Embankment stop of Northern Line, where all passengers can listen today and hear Oswald Laurence's voice and to think that eternal love really exists.

Fr Demetrius Gallitzin, Servant of God, born a Prince in the Russian Empire. His father, Prince Dimitri Alexeievixh, the Russia ambassador to the Netherlands. His mother was the Prussian Countess Amalie von Schmettau. At the age of 2 he was given a royal commission to the Russian Navy by Empress Catherine the Great. Entering adulthood he was called to the priesthood, but given his obligation to the Russia navy he had to flee to America to be ordained a priest. In America he was ordinated by Archbishop Carroll of Baltimore, but he soon become a pioneer missionary priest to the Allegheny Mountains. He established the first Catholic Church between Lancaster, PA and St Louis, MO. His most notable act is the well documented exorcism in Wizard Clip, WV. He was the only priest in the region for over 20 years, and he borrowed from his inheritance to help the local people to buy land, at a lost, and help established business in the area. Today he is known as the Apostle of the Alleghenies.

June signals the traditional start of Elderflower season. The above recipe is well worth the little effort and is far superior to shop bought Elderflower cordial. It's, in my opinion, the perfect Summers drink. Give it a go! (Don't be put off by the sugar content, this cordial can be diluted to taste and makes plenty!)
url_description: Homemade Elderflower cordial. Ingredients: - 2.5kg Sugar. - 50g citric acid. - 40 elderflower heads, stalks trimmed. - 2 Lemons, unwaxed. - 1.5 litres water. You will also need two large pans, funnel, ladle, colender, bottles (swingtop, corked, etc) and a tea towel. - Sterilise all equipment. - Heat the water and sugar in a pan, taking care to not boil and stir occasionally. - Meanwhile, shake off the flower heads to remove any insects, debris. You can dip them in water to help dislodge any hangers on but preferable not to, if possible. - zest the Lemons and then slice, leave to the side. - Once the sugar has dissolved, bring to the boil and turn off the heat. - Add the other ingredients and gently stir. - Cover the pan and leave for 24 hours. - After 24 hours, line a colender with the tea towel and place over a clean pan. Pour in the liquid. - Transfer this filtered liquid to bottles. Should keep for 6 weeks or can be frozen in plastic. Mix with Soda water for a sparkling summers drink. Enjoy.

Blackrock Castle, Ireland. Is a castellated fortification located at Blackrock, about 2 km from the centre of Cork city on the banks of the River Lee in Ireland. In the late 16th century, the citizens of Cork appealed to Queen Elizabeth I to construct a fort at Blackrock to "repel pirates and other invaders". In 1582 a fortification was built on the site, and later around 1600, a round tower was constructed to safeguard against pirates "carrying away" vessels entering the harbour. Blackrock Castle was in the ownership of the City of Cork following a charter of James I to the city in 1608. The castle is later referred to in the Council Book of Cork in 1613 and 1614. In 1722 the old four-storey tower was destroyed by fire and new one built by the citizens. Following a banquet, the castle was destroyed by fire in 1827. The rebuilding began at the direction of Mayor Thomas Dunscombe in 1828 and was completed in March 1829.

Jarlshof is the best known prehistoric archaeological site in Shetland, Scotland. It lies in Sumburgh, Mainland, Shetland and has been described as "one of the most remarkable archaeological sites ever excavated in the British Isles". It contains remains dating from 2500 BC up to the 17th century AD. The Bronze Age settlers left evidence of several small oval houses with thick stone walls and various artefacts including a decorated bone object. The Iron Age ruins include several different types of structures, including a broch and a defensive wall around the site. The Pictish period provides various works of art including a painted pebble and a symbol stone. The Viking Age ruins make up the largest such site visible anywhere in Britain and include a longhouse; excavations provided numerous tools and a detailed insight into life in Shetland at this time. The most visible structures on the site are the walls of the Scottish period fortified manor house

Scotland On the southern shore of the Bay o' Skaill you will find Skara Brae, a Neolithic settlement dating from circa5,000 years ago, it is a collection of eight Thatch and Sod covered Dwellings and additional covered spaces built in clover form around a central passage or main street if you like to call it that with connecting passages leading to the individual homes. The living spaces come with a very surprisingly high level of home comforts that include beds, dressers and even waterproof tanks for storing fresh seafood (or bait) within the homes. The settlement is thought to have been in use for several centuries and inhabited by between 50 to 100 people at any one time. Radiocarbon dating undertaken in the 1970s revealed that Skara Brae was in use from the late Neolithic, about 5,200 years ago, and in use for about 600 years until about 4,200 years ago, that would mark the date of the storm.

The disc, a single find from Hirschau, is divided into a central circle and seven edge segments by bridges. In the inner circle, a man is depicted on his knee with an object in his hand that can be interpreted as a drinking horn. A ribbon is tied around his neck leading to the center circle. Seven dragon/raptor heads form the outer circle. The animal ornamentation combined with braided ribbons is referred to as animal style II and appears in the Alamanic region from the second half of the 6th century. The man is interpreted as the god Wodan because of the noose around his neck. At the same time as Christian symbols, pagan protective symbols also appear on amulet-like objects from the 7th century in the Upper Gau. Both pagan and Christian symbols initially had the same function: apotropaic protection against demons and other dangers of everyday life.

Handfasting The phrase, "tying the knot", comes from ancient Northern European (Celtic/Nordic) tradition and culture - it was part of one of several wedding traditions in the ancient society. In pre-christian times, when a man and woman chose to be married, they were brought together in a ceremony to have a braided cord tied around their hands. This ritual was known as handfasting. The cords, or in some cases, ribbons, were made of different colored threads and decorated with small silver details, usually depicting typical motifs, such as a sword, ax, and different types of coins. This act acknowledged the pair's engagement, which typically ran the length of a year. It was a public declaration of intent to marry, signaling to potential suitors that the woman was intended to her betrothed and not to be harassed. After the year was up, the couple either declared their intent to be married or declared that they weren't a good match. Both would then be free to choose another suitor and bride.

Meteora Monasteries Location: Thessaly, #Greece The #Meteora is a rock formation in central Greece hosting one of the largest and most precipitously built complexes of Eastern #Orthodox monasteries, second in importance only to Mount Athos. Meteora is included on the #UNESCO World Heritage List. The exact date of the establishment of the monasteries is unknown. By the late eleventh and early twelfth centuries, a rudimentary monastic state had formed called the Skete of Stagoi and was centred around the still-standing church of #Theotokos (Mother of God). By the end of the twelfth century, an ascetic community had flocked to Meteora. At their peak in the sixteenth century there were 24 monasteries at Meteora in Greece. They were created to serve #monks and nuns following the teachings of the Eastern Orthodox #Church . Much of the #architecture of these buildings is #Athonite in origin. Today there are six still functioning.

url_title: Episode 5: Snob Screens (Britain's lost & living pubs)
url_description: We was lucky enough to pick the Lamb as our pub of choice when seeking a venue to show you what snob screens are. A wonderful and helpful ex-tour guide who works there gave us a walk through the pub and it's stunning features. This episode speaks of the class system of Victorian England and the methods used to keep the classes separated when in drinking venues. Snob screens can still be found in some British public houses since their use in the Victorian era. Usually installed in rows, they're made up of etched panes of glass in movable wooden frames. We had a wonderful day and deeply thank the staff at 'The Lamb' (Grade II listed pub at 94 Lamb's Conduit Street, Bloomsbury, London) and the kind reception we received. We cannot advise enough that you head down and enjoy this amazing location and take in it's inspiring history. Happy April 1st everyone! Gowk is Scots for cuckoo but is also known as the word for a fool. If you are called a huntegowk, then the joke was on you on April 1st. The Gowk Day custom derives in part from young people being led from wood to wood to track the newly arriving Spring cuckoos, with the ‚Äúhunt the gowk‚Äù always staged too early for the birds to be found. Typical Gowk Day pranks evolved from these fool‚Äôs errands. The traditional prank was to ask someone to deliver a sealed message requesting help of some sort. The sites are said to be linked to the heralding of spring and the arrival of the first cuckoo of the season. When the note was opened on delivery, the nature of the errand was revealed. ‚ÄúDinna laugh, dinna smile, hunt the gowk another mile,‚Äù was the message. The daft missions further evolved with reports of people being sent to the butcher for items such as a gill of pigeon milk. It is believed Gowk‚Äôs Day was marked in Scotland from at least 1700, according to accounts.

I believe it's important to remain as physically active as one can for more reasons than physical health or appearance. We must note, many who suffer from disabilities cannot do so to the same capacity or in some cases at all. To those whom this effects I deeply sympathise with you. But to those without the excuse, the use of one's body is to use up some of the less constructive energy and focus one's mind as a result. For many who struggle to sleep or struggle to contend with their inner thoughts, you may be feeling one's pent up capabilities playing out in a frustrated and unconstructive fashion. A tired feeling of success prepares one for rest and peaceful contemplation, as opposed to restless overloads of worry and unescapable stress. For this reason I cannot suggest enough one adopts some kind of physical hobby, if not for one's body then for one's mind. You owe it to yourself in the one life you're lucky enough to have. Always set up a small camera to observe your bird table, you never know what you will capture. Here, I have managed to record a Lesser Spotted Woodpecker visiting the feeder at a cottage on the banks of the Seiont river near Caernarfon, North Wales. The smallest and rarest of the three British woodpeckers, with less than 2,000 breeding pairs across the entirety of the isles. Wildlife can tell us a vast amount about the health of our local ecology, and many of the most incredible creatures are also the most elusive.

Rife as a feature in many folk tales, legends and British mysticism, King Alfred‚Äôs Cakes (or Coal Fungus) is a distinctive tinder bracket mushroom found widespread across the isles - particularly on fallen ash or beech branches. Named for the story of King Alfred, who, after taking up refuge with a peasant woman during wartime in exchange for watching over her fire as she baked small buns, burnt each and every one. Supposedly embarrassed and trying to cover his mistakes, the King took the pan and scattered the buns all across the forest. Easily identifiable by their striking round black fruiting bodies, each featuring concentric rings within, King Alfred‚Äôs Cakes is not only useful to us as a fire lighting forage but also for many bugs and insects to whom its ability to retain heat creates an ideal home.

The Landsker Line is a language border dividing Pembrokeshire and part of Carmarthenshire in south west Wales. 'Landsker' is an old English word denoting a land barrier of some kind. Fascinatingly, not only does the Landsker Line divide Pembrokeshire by language, but seemingly by blood too; with those south of the Landsker Line being genetically indistinguishable from the southern English. The accepted explanation for the Landsker division is that when the Normans arrived in England they colonised this part of Wales with Saxons, Normans and Flemings to form a stronghold. William of Malmesbury even claimed that all the Flemings of England were forced into an area of Pembrokeshire called 'The Hundred of Roose' (because England was apparently 'overburdened' with them). It is also suspected that some Norse and Irish settled in the region voluntarily, prior to the Norman invasion.

Beddgelert, a small village in the heart of the Snowdonia range and internationally recognised as one of the most beautiful villages in Europe. Named for the legend of the medieval Welsh Prince Llewelyn the Great and the tragic tale of his faithful hound, whose grave is tenderly watched over by residents of the village to this day. The story goes that in the 13th century, the Prince returned home from a hunting trip to find the cot of his only child empty, and his loyal friend, the hound Gelert, saturated with blood. Stricken with grief, Llewelyn plunged his sword deep into the dog's side. Only a moment later, the frantic Prince discovered the infant child shaken but unharmed lying next to the body of the wolf Gelert had slaughtered in an effort to protect the young heir. Prince Llewelyn was said to never have smiled again - burying the hound and dedicated the small village his name to honour his memory.

After seeing a few people discussing the state of Britain's hedges recently, this might be of interest to some. Hedge laying is an art, as with many things, that has been neglected in favour of inferior practices that are wrongly perceived to be more utilitarian. The farmer today neglects his hedges and then when the gaps appear he installs a fence and mows down the hedge in an indiscriminate manner, believing this to be easier for himself. The truth of the matter is that, in favour of short term time saving, the farmer is infact setting himself up for constant repair costs of a fence and the job of having to decimate the hedge every few years, rather than just laying the hedge once every two decades and trimming it in-between. The British hedgerow is something special. It is not merely just a boundary but a living tapestry that has helped define these lands for countless generations and has been a life line for much of our dwindling wildlife. This winter, the Twite - also known as the Pennine Finch - has been declared on the brink of extinction following a 5 year monitoring program of its few remaining nesting sites. Dwelling only in the South Pennine moorlands of Northern England, the studies revealed only 12 breeding pairs of the regional songbird remain. The Twite is one of only two bird species in the UK whose diet subsides of seeds alone, and are therefore reliant on the native biodiversity afforded by meadows and upland pasture that have seen increasing pesticide and agricultural damage over the last several decades. The evergreen Yew is the longest-lived tree species in Britain. Outdating even the beloved Oak tree, it is impossible to tell exactly how old it‚Äôs most ancient individuals are (due to the withering of the heartwood preventing traditional ring-dating techniques after around 500 years), however it is thought that we can roughly estimate the age of the tree based on its girth. It is estimated that a Yew tree of 30ft in girth may be up to 2,400 years old, and 35ft of being up to 4,500 years old. It is estimated that our oldest living specimens in the Isles today are between 3,000 - 5,000 years old. Episode 5: Snob Screens (Britain's lost & living pubs) We was lucky enough to pick the Lamb as our pub of choice when seeking a venue to show you what snob screens are. A wonderful and helpful ex-tour guide who works there gave us a walk through the pub and it's stunning features. This episode speaks of the class system of Victorian England and the methods used to keep the classes separated when in drinking venues. Snob screens can still be found in some British public houses since their use in the Victorian era. Usually installed in rows, they're made up of etched panes of glass in movable wooden frames. We had a wonderful day and deeply thank the staff at 'The Lamb' (Grade II listed pub at 94 Lamb's Conduit Street, Bloomsbury, London) and the kind reception we received. We cannot advise enough that you head down and enjoy this amazing location and take in it's inspiring history.

Robins are commonly associated with the Christmas time, despite being present and active across the Isles all year round - although an established figure of the festive season as we know it today, the link is actually a fairly modern adoption. The tradition comes from the Victorian era when posting Christmas cards first became a common habit of the British folk. Our iconic red post boxes featured as a central theme in the art displayed on many cards as the Royal Mail (and postmen themselves) acted a symbol of remaining connected to those we love over the season. Over time, the postmen and their bright red uniform commonly became known as ‚Äúred breasts‚Äù. From there the association naturally passed from the red breasted mailman to the beloved robin redbreast as we know them. As their vivid hues stand stark against a cover of snow, over time the robin came to symbolise the postman and replaced them as a central theme in traditional English Christmas art.

DIY Winter Wreath Step 4 - adding Decoration: at this stage your creativity and personal taste can lead the way. You can add pinecones by wrapping a small length of wire between its largest segments, and sticking the sharp ends into your base through your foliage. Add berries by binding wire around their stalks, or baked orange slice by poking the wire through a translucent segment, and fitting them much the same way. I used a green wire so it would become invisible amongst the foliage, and it worked really well! You can add bows, feathers, flowers, branches, dried leaves, anything at all that you find beautiful. The important thing is that all sharp ends are hidden away, tucked neatly into your base. Once you‚Äôve decorated with the best of your forage, you‚Äôre ready to hang! Dried wreaths will last for many years, and naturally offer a great deal more festive spirit and sentimentality when made from scratch with local materials.

DIY Winter Wreath Step 3 - adding Foliage: arrange your materials however you please, securing it to your wreath using the same continuous twine binding method you used on the base, always giving a firm tug as you feed the twine back towards yourself. If you have evergreen foliage like me, you‚Äôll want to build bunches roughly the size and width of your hand, and arrange them on the wreath with their stems facing towards you, layering one bushy end over the previous additions stems. Tie around each bunch as many times as you feel you need, I do 5 or 6 binds around each. Continue this process until you have a full wreath - this step took me around an hour and a half.

DIY Winter Wreath Step 2 - the Hook: simply cut 6 pieces of twine roughly 15‚Äù long, hold them together and tie a knot in the top. Divide the lengths into 3 and braid as you can see above. This will be what you use to hang the wreath! Tie both ends of this close together around the inner ring; wrap a short length of wire around the knots and ring to reinforce the hold. Tuck any lose wire ends away by pushing them into your base, no sharp ends should be exposed.

DIY Winter Wreath I apologise in advance for not taking pictures of each step of the way - I enjoyed making my wreath in the good company of some local ladies and got caught up in the festivities of it all! Hopefully my step by step guide is still useful. Step 1 - the Base: As you see here I used a moss base around a copper ring. You can also wind together a base using wood from Cedar, willow, dogwood, poplar or birch, use oasis foam or straw - or buying premade is an option too. Whatever you use, your goal will be to tightly bind your material to a ring using twine. As you feed the twine through the hoop and back towards yourself, tug hard to tighten it as much as possible and finish by tying a tight and firm double knot around the inner ring.

After being captured by the foreign forces, Edmund was beaten, shot to death with arrows, and beheaded after refusing to forsake his land and faith. Followers of the warrior king sought his remains, supposedly finding the severed head guarded by an ethereal wolf chanting ‚ÄúHere, here, here‚Äù. Otherwise known as Deadman‚Äôs Day, on 20th November we revere not only St Edmund but all men and sacrificial kings who laid down their lives for their land and people.

Elizabeth Southerns and Anne Whittle, better known as the Pendle Witches, are still said to haunt the landscape. The Grey Partridge, also known as the Grey Bird, Girgirick and simply, Stumpey, is the Isles only native game bird. Partridge are a member of the pheasant family, and as suggested by it‚Äôs more colloquial names, the bird is a small, heavily-built bird with short wings and a short, strong beak. The bird is immensely popular in both sport and on the dinner table, as a result protection and proclamation orders have been placed on the species repeatedly through out history in order to protect its numbers. This has been less than effective as hunting for sport increased in popularity; Grey Partridge are now threatened in the UK, with less than 30% of chicks making it adulthood despite laying large clusters of up to 22 eggs at a time.

It‚Äôs currently seal pupping season - which means those of us living on or visiting the coast may need to take extra care near the shore. We are home to both common and grey seals, both of which must rest on land in order to digest, socialise and feed their pups. Seals are very easily startled and often injure themselves when attempting swift escapes from perceived threats. Especially at this time of year when protecting and providing for their young, seals are especially vulnerable. Never approach a seal or it‚Äôs pup, the general rule of thumb is that if a seal looks at you - you‚Äôre putting it at risk. We have already lost up to 50% of our seal population since 2000 - a staggering decline behind which we are yet to identify the cause, but human interference almost certainly plays its part. Stay back, stay quiet and stay out of sight. And if you see anyone else pestering, do your part to protect these docile and vulnerable natives.

In Germanic mythology, Seaxnƒìat or Saxn≈çt is the national god of the Saxons. The Old English form Seaxnƒìat is recorded in the genealogies of the kings of Essex. The Old Saxon form Saxn≈çt is attested in the Old Saxon Baptismal Vow along with the gods Woden and Thonar. The genealogy of the kings of Essex originally placed Seaxnƒìat at its apex. It was subsequently modified to make Seaxnƒìat son of Woden, with the first king of Essex seven generations later. The name is usually derived from "seax", the eponymous knife which was characteristic of the tribe, and (ge)-not, (ge)-nƒìat as "companion" (cognate with German Genosse "comrade"), resulting in a translation of "sword-companion".

CROW, ROOK or RAVEN? These three large corvidae birds are extremely similar in their appearance, especially from afar, so here are a few ways to tell the difference: CROW ‚Ä¢ Smaller solid black beak with slight bill feathering ‚Ä¢ Tends to roam in large groups (murders) ‚Ä¢ Smooth plumage, particularly around head and throat ‚Ä¢ Tail feathers even in length, forming a fan shape ROOK ‚Ä¢ Large pale, straight beak with no feathering ‚Ä¢ Roams and lives in large rookeries ‚Ä¢ Long wings that narrow towards the body ‚Ä¢ Feathery trousers RAVEN ‚Ä¢ Large, rounded black beak with distinct bill feathers ‚Ä¢ Seen alone or with their mate only ‚Ä¢ Shaggy plumage around the head, throat and breast ‚Ä¢ Long, diamond shaped tail

Wild Boar (Sus Scrofa) A creature of myth and magic, the Wild Boar has been revered across the Isles for thousands of years. Honoured for its strength and courage, the boar (Eofor) features on many ancient heraldic crests. In the Isles, Wild Boar are closely associated with the ‚Äòotherworld‚Äô; linked with folk idols as Fionn Mac Cumhaill, Culhwch & Olwen, and Odin, the creature was a precious totem for those of a warrior or hunter persuasion. Amongst wise folk, the tusks of the boar were coveted as greatly powerful in keeping away malignant forces as well as an aid for women during child birth, their bristles would be boiled with fresh water in copper cauldrons to conjure rain and storms, and it‚Äôs flesh would be ritually consumed to impart valour and victory when going into battle.

url_description: The Black Mere of Morridge, also called Blake Mere Pond, or The Mermaid Pool, is a small lake in North Staffordshire; which legend says is inhabited by a dangerous Mermaid, the subject of many Ghost Stories. Sitting approximately six miles North-West of the town of Leek in Staffordshire, legend and local folklore tell that the malicious mermaid is beautiful beyond measure and has led many young men to their deaths. In this video I explore the origins both of the mermaid and the lake, as well as several unsettling events that have taken place on its banks. The stories told of the mermaid origin are not sourced on verifiable information, surviving in local oral tradition and being committed to paper on occasion. As such the version of events I re-tell in this video are not exactly the original legends, which can be found elsewhere, rather I have lengthened and embellished the stories for the purposes of entertainment, and to include elements of similar if not identical stories about the mermaids origin. #TheRoaches #PeakDistrict #Mermaid #GhostStories A big thank you to Mrs Staffordshire Folklore for the drawing of the mermaid. Paris held his judgement on Mount Ida, where the three goddesses were accompanied by Hermes (Mercury) as their guide. Paris first inspected them clothed; as he was unable to make a decision, the three of them removed their clothing and offered Paris their bribes. Hera offered to make him king of both Europe and Asia, and Athena plied him with wisdom and skill at war. But it was Aphrodite‚Äôs inducement to which Paris succumbed: she offered him the most beautiful woman in the world, Helen, then the wife of the Greek king Menelaus. The consequence of Paris‚Äôs (ill) judgement was that he abducted Helen and took her to Troy, which was the immediate cause of the Greek war against Troy. After conversion to Christianity, Eris has lived on as a personification, referred to as Dame Discord in Ariosto‚Äôs Orlando Furioso.

Jacob Jordaens (1593‚Äì1678), The Golden Apple of Discord (1633), oil on canvas, 181 √ó 288 cm, Museo Nacional del Prado, Madrid, Spain. Wikimedia Commons. In The Golden Apple of Discord, the facially discordant Eris, seen in midair behind the deities, has just made her gift of the golden apple, which is at the centre of the grasping hands, above the table. At the left, Minerva (Pallas Athene) reaches forward for it. In front of her, Aphrodite, her son Eros at her knee, points to herself as the goddess most deserving of the apple. On the other side of the table, Hera reaches her hand out for it too.

Eris then gatecrashed the wedding celebration, and as she passed through lobbed her golden apple between Hera, Athena and Aphrodite, making it the reward for a beauty contest between them. Joachim Wtewael (1566‚Äì1638), The Wedding of Peleus and Thetis (date not known), oil on copper, 36.5 x 42 cm, The Clark Art Institute, Williamstown, MA. Wikimedia Commons. Joachim Wtewael‚Äôs undated painting of The Wedding of Peleus and Thetis is great fun with its aerial band, and numerous glimpses of deities behaving badly. Eris is here about to throw her apple of discord into their midst: she is in mid-air to the left of centre, the apple held out in her right hand. The clearest and finest depiction of the role of Eris was made by Jacob Jordaens in 1633, after a brilliant oil sketch by Rubens.

Joseph Mallord William Turner (1775‚Äì1851), The Goddess of Discord Choosing the Apple of Contention in the Garden of the Hesperides (1806), oil on canvas, 155.3 x 218.4 cm, The Tate Gallery (Accepted by the nation as part of the Turner Bequest 1856), London. ¬© The Tate Gallery and Photographic Rights ¬© Tate (2017), CC-BY-NC-ND 3.0 (Unported), http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/turner-the-goddess-of-discord-choosing-the-apple-of-contention-in-the-garden-of-the-n00477 Eris decided to take a special present to the wedding feast: a golden apple which she chose from the Garden of the Hesperides. JMW Turner‚Äôs The Goddess of Discord Choosing the Apple of Contention in the Garden of the Hesperides from 1806 shows Eris as an older woman dressed in a red skirt, in the centre foreground. She is choosing between two golden apples which have just been picked from the surrounding garden by her sisters the Hesperides.

Nicolas Poussin (1594‚Äì1665), Time Defending Truth against the Attacks of Envy and Discord (1641), oil on canvas, diam 297 cm, Mus√©e du Louvre, Paris. Wikimedia Commons. ~ Poussin‚Äôs later tondo Time Defending Truth against the Attacks of Envy and Discord (1641) puts Father Time at its centre, with a firm grip around Truth‚Äôs waist, while Envy and Discord sit below them, the latter with snakes in her hair resembling Medusa. Most other appearances of Eris are in her role as the initiator of the Judgement of Paris. Myths tell that she was omitted from the guest list for the wedding of Peleus and Thetis, which was celebrated by all the other deities.

Peter Paul Rubens (1577‚Äì1640), The Triumph of Victory (c 1614), oil on oak panel, 161 x 236 cm, Gem√§ldegalerie Alte Meister, Kassel, Germany. Wikimedia Commons. This work was commissioned by the Antwerp Guild of St George, its organisation of archers, so the figure of Mars dominates. His bloody sword rests on the thigh of Victoria, personification of victory. She reaches over to place a wreath (of either oak or laurel) on Mars, and holds a staff in her left hand. At the right, Mars is being passed the bundle of crossbow bolts that make up the attribute of Concord. Under the feet of Mars are the bodies of Rebellion, in the foreground, who still holds his torch, and Discord, on whose cheek a snake is crawling. The bound figure resting against the left knee of Mars is Barbarism.

Jacob Jordaens (1593‚Äì1678), The Golden Apple of Discord (1633), oil on canvas, 181 √ó 288 cm, Museo Nacional del Prado, Madrid, Spain. Wikimedia Commons. The last of the children of Nyx, primordial goddess of night, who has any significant presence in art since the Renaissance is Eris, associated with either strife or discord, and known to the Romans as Discordia. Eris is best known for setting up the Judgement of Paris, thus leading the Greeks to war with the Trojans, but this isn‚Äôt her sole role in paintings. Some older sources draw distinction between Eris as strife, and her personification of discord. This isn‚Äôt clear from her appearance in paintings, though. One notable appearance is in Peter Paul Rubens‚Äô The Triumph of Victory (c 1614), made when he was young, and the finest painter in Flanders. On this day in 1687 Francesco Morosini fired one round scoring a hit on the Parthenon. The 15-year Great Turkish War was made up of smaller conflicts, such as the Morean War between Venice & the Turks. The Acropolis proved a troublesome target. The Turks were dug in on the summit having fortified the site. Pericles‚Äô Propylaea was still in ruins following the explosion of a powder magazine in 1656. Instead it was the Parthenon that presented Morosini with the most logical target. Despite the earlier destruction of the Propylaea the Parthenon was being used by the Turks as a gunpowder store possibly believing that the site was protected by the sheer weight of history. This wasn't the case. On 26 September 1687 Morosini fired one round scoring a hit on the powder magazine inside the Parthenon. The explosion caused the cella to collapse, blowing out the central part of the walls & bringing down much of Phidias‚Äô frieze. Many columns also toppled causing the architraves, triglyphs & metopes to come tumbling down.

Carneddau Ponies Isolated as a species for hundreds of years, the distinctive Carneddau Ponies of the Welsh mountains are an incredibly rare, genetically unique and primitive British wild horse. Existing only in the Carneddau mountains of Snowdonia, there are only around 300 of these horses in the world. The Carneddau Ponies range only around 20 square miles of harsh mountain terrain, where they have remained since the Bronze Age. As a result of their harsh native climate and thorough pedigree following centuries of seclusion from other wild horses, the ponies stand at only 10 hands high and are known for their incredible hardiness and ability to withstand even the most severe conditions.

The Treason of the Long Knives (Welsh: Brad y Cyllyll Hirion) was a pseudohistorical myth and legend of a massacre of British Celtic chieftains by Anglo-Saxon soldiers at a peace conference on Salisbury Plain in the 5th century. The story is not included in any contemporary accounts, but does feature centuries later in the semi-mythological histories of the Historia Brittonum and the Historia Regum Britanniae. According to the tradition, Vortigern, who had become a high king of the Britons in the wake of the end of Roman rule in Britain, called for Anglo-Saxons under Hengist and Horsa to settle on the Isle of Thanet in exchange for their service as mercenaries in battles against the Picts and Gaels in Scotland. The settlers, however, exploit a drunken Vortigern's lust for Hengist's daughter into allowing them to increase their numbers and granting them more land, eventually including all of the Kingdom of Kent.

So these are the remedies I used to get over my bout of sickness. I hope this is useful to you if you find yourself taken down by something similar. They may also be useful to take in anticipation of Autumn/Winter, to maintain a healthy immune defence. It's impossible to tell which of these worked and which didn't. I threw everything at it. Many of these are naturally-occurring, age-old medicines. In no particular order: ‚Ä¢ Sea Kelp (Iodine): Antiseptic, protection from toxins. ‚Ä¢ Oregano Oil: Natural antibiotic. ‚Ä¢ Quercetin: Immune system health. ‚Ä¢ Quinine (in the form of tonic water): Anti-fever, anti-inflammation. ‚Ä¢ Hydroxycloroquine (related to Quinine): I only took a couple of tablets so likely didn't help. ‚Ä¢ Vitamin D: Immune system health. ‚Ä¢ Mullein Leaf: Respiratory health. ‚Ä¢ Zinc: Immune system health. ‚Ä¢ Turmeric: Anti-inflammatory. ‚Ä¢ High dose Vitamin C: Immune system health. ‚Ä¢ Ivermectin: 'Antiparasitic'. My brother had been ill not long before me and posted me his leftover Ivermectin to try. ‚Ä¢ Paracetamol and Ibuprofen, rotated: I always prefer to avoid taking these for headaches and things. But during this bout of illness they kept my fever in check so I took them regularly. Other actions that did help, or may have: ‚Ä¢ Plenty of sleep and rest. ‚Ä¢ We bought a little oxygen cylinder to try and get my oxygen levels up. This was helpful when I needed to move, as taking in some extra oxygen before doing so stopped me from feeling so light-headed. ‚Ä¢ My wife made me a broth with onion, garlic, turmeric and kale which I was able to drink even when I had no appetite whatsoever. These ingredients are natural antibiotics. ‚Ä¢ Spending time in direct sunlight. ‚Ä¢ Keeping myself as cool as possible, to prevent over-heating. This is difficult to do when you wake up in a freezing cold sweat, but necessary. ‚Ä¢ Also, to add, I got myself a himalayan salt inhaler recently. This might be good to use during such an illness. Salt cleanses through air and moisture as it does through water. If you know of other remedies, please share in the comments.

Let‚Äôs have a look at 0% fat products and if/when we should be eating them. On the surface, it may seem that less fat in your foods = less body fat, but this isn‚Äôt the case. Fats help our bodies process vitamins and nutrients, synthesise hormones, store energy and more. Rather than reducing fats in our diet, to reduce our body weight we should be aiming for active calorie deficit. Now, every 1g of fat contains 9 calories, versus protein and carbs which contain only 4 calories per gram. So it may seem that 0% fat means fewer calories by default - but actually, it doesn‚Äôt. All 0% products increase carbs to balance the loss of fats from the product, meaning the calorie contents are often pretty much the same. That doesn‚Äôt mean there are no benefits, however. Carbs and proteins both digest quicker than fat does, meaning reduced fat foods are perfect to eat before/during activities. This will allow your body to extract the nutrients and energy you need quickly, without making you feel sluggish! @Viribusfemale

The Legend of the Hartlepool ‚ÄòMonkey Hanging‚Äô. In the early 19th century, during the Napoleonic wars, a French ship was spotted sinking off the Hartlepool (Durham) coast. Wary of the enemy ship, the town's inhabitants ran down to the shore and discovered the ship's only survivor; a ship monkey dressed in a miniature military uniform. During the wars the French would often be characterised as monkeys. So it‚Äôs forgivable to think that the good folk may have believed that the monkey was a French spy. As a result a trial was held to ascertain whether the monkey was guilty or not and, seeing as the monkey was unavailable to defend himself, he was found guilty. He was subsequently dragged through the town and hanged. However, the story may not be as simple as that. During this time many young boys would often be hired on ships to prime cannons with gunpowder and they garnered the nickname ‚Äòpowder-monkeys‚Äô. So could the story of the Hartlepool monkey simply be an event that was misconstrued through time or a genuine tale of an animal experiencing capital punishment? Whatever the true story may be, the tale of the Hartlepool Monkey lives on and resides in the consciousness of the town's inhabitants today as it did two centuries ago.

If weight loss or fitness improvements have stalled, one important factor to consider is your NEAT output. NEAT: Non-Exercise Activity Thermogenesis - or in other words, all the activity you do in the day that is not exercising. This makes up 85-99% of your activity per day, and so making small changes to your average routine can make a huge difference to your goals. Some easy ways to improve your NEAT output: ‚Ä¢ Always take the stairs ‚Ä¢ Walk instead of driving where you can ‚Ä¢ Turn on some music and dance while you cook ‚Ä¢ Go for a leisurely walk of 30 mins or more each day ‚Ä¢ Be more social and expressive, walk, laugh and chat more ‚Ä¢ Walk to local shops and carry back groceries ‚Ä¢ Be conscious of sitting too long

Dragon Hill and St. George Uffington in Berkshire is teeming with legends and lore: The White Horse, Wayland's Smithy and Dragon Hill. Here it is said that King Arthur's father Uther Pendragon had been buried, the hill his kingly barrow, but the concentration of treasure had attracted a dragon who as dragons are want to do took up residence in the mound by day and by night ravaged the North Wessex Downs. The local king eventually offered his own daughter Princess Sadra to the dragon as a sacrifice but she was rescued from her fate by a gallant young knight who slew the dragon on the hill and who's acidic blood to this day makes the grass grow poorly. The king asked the knight his name and replied: George and in reward took Sadra's hand in marriage. Our ancient ancestors knew this site as Eccles Beorh or Church Barrow, implying a religious site that was likely built on a Pre-Christian sacred location.

Hoodening Dating back to the early 18th century, the Hoodening or Hooden Horse is a yule time folk custom in Kent. The Hoodening centres around a wooden hobby horse - a common folk custom across England - carried through the town by a man cloaked in a dark sack cloth. With a hinged jaw operated on a string, the horse would growl and snap and prance along with the tune of Christmas carols. Traditionally made up of local farm labourers and horse handlers, the Hooden Horse would be paraded alongside its procession, which included the Groom, who would lead the horse by its bridle, a Jockey that would attempt to ride the horse, a man dressed as a woman known as the ‚ÄòMollie‚Äô who would scare away young girls, and one or two dancers and musicians. The horse and it‚Äôs band would go door to door at Christmas performing for the locals, as well as through the markets, to which the residents of Kent would typically reward the Hooden Horse in money, food and drink.

However, habitat destruction, road deaths and irresponsible land management still threatens the species. As of 2006, more than 70% of known barn owl nesting sites were artificially constructed for purpose. This number shows the devastating lack of natural habitat remaining for these unique birds, and how important setting up bird nesting boxes on private land can be to saving our native species.

Dragon of Mordiford One of the most remarkable accounts of British dragons, the Dragon of Mordiford tells of a young girl named Maud who discovered a baby dragon in the woods of Mordiford, Herefordshire. The child was forbidden from caring for the creature, but in secrecy she fed, groomed and nurtured the beast as it grew. Ultimately, as is always the way with dragons, in adolescence and adulthood the beast could not contain its carnivorous urges and began picking apart the townsfolk and their livestock, protecting only the girl who had raised it. Despite pleading for its life, the dragon was slain by a local convict who also died in the battle. The story of Mordiford‚Äôs dragon has survived throughout the ages, passed from generation to generation. Many locals still claim familial connection to the legend and hold steadfast in their belief that the story is much more than an old legend, and that the village of Mordiford was truly once home to one of the last dragons in England.

Locals speak of the voices of the dead on the swirling winds of the pass following an infamous murder in the mid 1700s. The story of Alan & Clara tells of a young couple seeking marriage against the will of their families. Heading to Peak Forest Chapel to elope, the pair were noticed by a surly group of miners in a Castleton tavern. The miners followed, robbed and brutally murdered the pair, stashing the bodies deep within the Winnat‚Äôs Pass cave system where they would not be found for over 10 years. The miners didn‚Äôt get away with their crimes however. One is said to have fallen from a cliff, another hit by a falling stone, one went mad and committed suicide, the last so guilt-ridden that he confessed it all on his deathbed. The graves of Alan & Clara remain at St Edmunds, Castleton, with the brides‚Äô very own red leather saddle on display still at Stonewell Cavern Museum.

url_title: EXTREMELY Rare Whisky Hip Flask Restoration - World War II
url_description: Restoration of an extremely rare World War 2 whisky hip flask found in a barn yard in the battlefields of Bulge. This is a Memorial Day edition to honour the fallen soldiers of World War 2 ‚ù§ About this Whisky hip flask I have never seen something like this before. It is beyond cool. I have bought it from a family who lives near Bastogne where the actual battle of Bulge took place in 1944. I got this whisky hip flask and a lot of other really cool relics with me home this time including a Medic bag and a Medic helmet (unfortunately the family has already had the helmet restored a few years back). This family has been living in Bastogne for many generations, and I was told that after the battles there was military ‚Äúgarbage‚Äù (war relics) left all over the place. You can still go to France, Poland, Germany, Russia, Belgium ‚Äì yep most of Europe and do some awesome World War 1 and World War 2 founds. There were millions of military items left behind. The restoration process I know this is a special one, so I saved it for the US Memorial Day 2021. It was with a mix of respect and fear of not being able to restore this beautiful and rare whisky hip flask that I started this restoration. First, I Cleaned this relic with alcohol and soap and removed the WW2 Combat Medicine badge with blow torch. I was very careful not to melt the pewter and destroy the whisky flask. I soaked the badge in Russian vodka ‚ÄúRocket fuel‚Äù. I fixed and repaired a big dent in the bottom of the hip flask. For that I used heat and gentle hammer strokes. I prepared the hip flask for casting by grinding and cleaning the big hole there was in this hip flask and fill it with casting sand. I filled the hole in the flask with pewter and after that I hand grinded it back to as good as it gets. I did a quick polish and attached the World War 2 Combat Medicine badge again and filled the hip flask with the VAT. 69 whisky which some of the soldiers used to drink in 1944. I really liked this restoration and I hope that you enjoy this video. Please subscribe if you want to see more cool upcoming projects üôÇ And DON‚ÄôT FORGET TO SEE my EXTREMELY RARE WW2 D-DAY LIGHTER RESTORATION - https://youtu.be/NXEl-Pqqo60 Thanks for watching my channel. See you soon. Best wishes and stay safe ‚ù§ Martin Music: From YouTube free audio library. And from paid licence at EnvatoElements.

Cream together the sugar and butter until pale in colour. Add the eggs, cinnamon and half the flour. Gradually add the cider to this mixture and lastly add the remaining flour and mix thoroughly. Pour into a greased 8" round cake tin and bake for approximately 45 mins or until firm to the touch and golden brown in colour. If desired then wait until cake is cool and dust with icing sugar. Pine Martens are a keystone predator in the British Isles, helping to protect habitats and native wildlife by preying on invasive species like the grey squirrel. Unlike their foreign cousins, red squirrels are not at risk from pine martens because they are too spicy‚Ä¶ just kidding! Red squirrels and pine martens have cohabited in woodland for millennia, and in wilder landscapes where food was plentiful, pine martens simply never developed the habit to prey on them. However, grey squirrels entered our ecosystem later, and were introduced to the UK during a time where habitats and natural resources were reducing by the day, making the larger and more rowdy species a favourite meal for the hungry mustelids.

Stirling Memorial Library, Yale University. Completed in 1930, it was designed by architect James Gamble Rogers (Yale Class of 1889) and later named for its benefactor, John William Sterling (Yale Class of 1864). It currently houses more than 2.5 million on 16 floors of book stacks. It was built in the Collegiate Gothic style, resembling a European Gothic cathedral, with its 60-foot ceiling, cloisters, clerestory windows, side chapels, and a circulation desk altar. The stained glass windows throughout the building, 3,300 in all, were designed by artist G. Owen Bonawit. SML houses the Irving S. Gilmore Music Library, added in 1998, as well as numerous reading rooms and departments.

Wildflower of the week: Common Hogweed. Common Hogweed, aka Cows Parsnip (and easier to find online as such), is a common flower of verges and fields. Some specimens can grow 7-8 feet! The flowers are attractive to Ladybirds and butterflies. They usually flower between June and August and produce an average of 5,000 seeds per head. The leaves can grow to be 16 inches long and are edible. The leaves are best cooked in butter like a green. You MUST, however, make sure that you have correctly identified the plant and have not mistaken it for it's very dangerous cousin Giant Hogweed. Giant Hogweed can cause long term blistering and photosensitivity that can leave you unable to go into the sun. You can thank our 19th century ancestors for bringing this dangerous plant over from Asia and letting it escape.

The tale of Only Me There was once a stone cottage stood on on the edge of the wild, where lived a widow and her son. All night and day the mother would work herself to the bone to keep her idle boy fed, and when the days came to an end she bade him join her and go to bed. " No Mother, I'm not going to bed yet it's not even that late!" He would rage and rant. Well one stormy night the boy's mother couldn't be bothered with his whining anymore and went abed without him crying "Fine stay awake" she snapped "you won't like it when it gets dark and the Faeries come out to get you!". The boy scoffed, he was too old for such nonsense and besides he would lie by the fire away from the dark. However the boy, as is the way with young boys, grew bored and restlessly drummed his feel on the hearth as he let out a loud sigh. At this the fireplace shifted and a reedy voice cried out "What's the matter with you then!?" The boy jumped - This wasn't his mother, so ... who was it? "Who... who's there?" He whispered. "It's only me!" cried a voice and all at once in a spray of ash an elf-girl leapt from the fire. She was small, no bigger than his hand with hair the bleached gold of dead grass and clothes the colour of sodden peat. He reached out in fearful curiosity and prodded her lightly. At once she spat at him: "Oi, don't you poke me! Who do you think you are?? What's your name!?" The boy, knowing well the tricks of elves refused to say. The elf, growing angry demanded again " Tell me or I'll put a evil spell on you!". The boy thought to himself, well maybe I can play at her game "I'm ... I'm Only Me!". The elf-girl gave a coarse laugh. "I like that! I'll grant you a wish!" The boy thought and then eagerly cried "I wish for some magic tricks!" The Elf-Girl nodded and immediately grasped a handful of ashes from the fire. She spat on it, kneaded it into animals the size of a thumbnail - a rat, a wolf a badger and a weasel. They immediately grew and came to life. The boy astonished could say nothing. The elf-girl frowned at this "What, not impressed? Fine. Stoke up the fire its growing cold!". The bot picked up the poker and half-heartedly poked at the fire. "Bash it you weakling" she snapped. He brought the poker down heavily and whoosh a spray of cinders cascaded across the fireplace and onto the elf-girls foot! The girl let out a terrible shriek that was after a moment of terrible silence answered with an eerie booming voice from within the fire itself! "Who's that? What's the matter?" The terrible voice intoned. "It's only me mother! cried the elf-girl in response "He burned my foot!". "Did he now daughter? Well you just tell me who he is and I'll cast terrible spells upon him and his family!" The voice growled, now dripping with terrible malice. The boy shrank back behind a nearby chair and held his breath. "Who did it mother? Why it was Only Me!" The elf girl cried , her eyes alight with cruel excitement. The hidden one let out a groan "Why you foolish child why didn't you just say??" Suffenly in a burst of a long pale arm shot from the chimney and snatched the elf-girl in a hooked paw before dragging her still protesting into the fire. As she did so the fire collapsed and went out with a poof of soot and after a moment of trembling stillness the boy shot up the ladder and climbed straight into bed beside his poor mother. You can be sure he never saw anything like that again, and for every night for the rest of his life he would he sure to go to bed early.

Model of the Monastery of St Caol√°n, known as "Aon Droim" that lent its name to county Antrim. The concentric walls were defensive to repel any attacks by heathens, the roundtower was where women, children and the elderly retreated to for safety while the monks defended the monastery from attack. Farming was integral to Gaelic Monastery life, Irish monks were well known across the continent for their work rate. The Axe was the most common weapon used by Irish monks, a tool "they wielded as confidently as ink and pen".

1st July Feast of St Oliver Plunkett (1625 - 1681) Archbishop of Armagh & primate of All Ireland Having been hung, drawn and quartered, his head was eventually recovered from the fire and Dom Maurus Corker had it smuggled to the Benedictine Monastery in Lamspringe, Germany. It then passed on to Cardinal Philip Howard OP at Rome, a friend of St. Oliver, who had helped the Archbishop of Armagh to return to Ireland safely after his ordination as Archbishop. From him, it passed to Oliver‚Äôs successor, Archbishop of Armagh Hugh McMahon, who returned the head to its rightful place in Ireland. McMahon brought the head to the Dominican Nuns at Siena, the prioress at the time being Sister Catherin Plunkett, St. Oliver‚Äôs grand niece. The sisters kept the head in good condition for a further 200 years at this point, before it arrived St. Peter‚Äôs Parish Church in Drogheda. 'Sherwood' by Alfred Noyes Sherwood in the twilight, is Robin Hood awake? Grey and ghostly shadows are gliding through the brake, Shadows of the dappled deer, dreaming of the morn, Dreaming of a shadowy man that winds a shadowy horn. Robin Hood is here again: all his merry thieves Hear a ghostly bugle-note shivering through the leaves, Calling as he used to call, faint and far away, In Sherwood, in Sherwood, about the break of day. Merry, merry England has kissed the lips of June: All the wings of fairyland were here beneath the moon, Like a flight of rose-leaves fluttering in a mist Of opal and ruby and pearl and amethyst. Merry, merry England is waking as of old, With eyes of blither hazel and hair of brighter gold: For Robin Hood is here again beneath the bursting spray In Sherwood, in Sherwood, about the break of day. Love is in the greenwood building him a house Of wild rose and hawthorn and honeysuckle boughs: Love is in the greenwood, dawn is in the skies, And Marian is waiting with a glory in her eyes. Hark! The dazzled laverock climbs the golden steep! Marian is waiting: is Robin Hood asleep? Round the fairy grass-rings frolic elf and fay, In Sherwood, in Sherwood, about the break of day. Oberon, Oberon, rake away the gold, Rake away the red leaves, roll away the mould, Rake away the gold leaves, roll away the red, And wake Will Scarlett from his leafy forest bed. Friar Tuck and Little John are riding down together With quarter-staff and drinking-can and grey goose-feather. The dead are coming back again, the years are rolled away In Sherwood, in Sherwood, about the break of day. Softly over Sherwood the south wind blows. All the heart of England his in every rose Hears across the greenwood the sunny whisper leap, Sherwood in the red dawn, is Robin Hood asleep? Hark, the voice of England wakes him as of old And, shattering the silence with a cry of brighter gold Bugles in the greenwood echo from the steep, Sherwood in the red dawn, is Robin Hood asleep? Where the deer are gliding down the shadowy glen All across the glades of fern he calls his merry men-- Doublets of the Lincoln green glancing through the May In Sherwood, in Sherwood, about the break of day-- Calls them and they answer: from aisles of oak and ash Rings the Follow! Follow! and the boughs begin to crash, The ferns begin to flutter and the flowers begin to fly, And through the crimson dawning the robber band goes by. Robin! Robin! Robin! All his merry thieves Answer as the bugle-note shivers through the leaves, Calling as he used to call, faint and far away, In Sherwood, in Sherwood, about the break of day.

Wildflower of the week: Corncockle. Although not a true native, Corncockle has been naturalised since it was brought over 2,400 years ago. Once a common weed in cereal crops, corncockle has declined severely due to modern grain screening practices, as cornfield annuals have a symbiotic life cycle with traditional agricultural pracitices which render them at a severe disadvantage in the wild or in a modern agricultural setting. On the flip side, the seeds are toxic and were responsible for many people being sick from contaminated grain, some cases being fatal. Still, it's a real shame this once common wildflower has all but dissapeared in the wild. It can still be found in many gardens and purposely sown as an annual in cornfields. https://plantlife.love-wildflowers.org.uk/wildflower_garden/grow_in_the_garden/corncockle

url_description: CANDIDE by Voltaire - FULL AudioBook | Greatest Audio Books Candide, ou l'Optimisme is a French satire first published in 1759 by Voltaire, a philosopher of the Age of Enlightenment. The novella has been widely translated, with English versions titled Candide: or, All for the Best (1759); Candide: or, The Optimist (1762); and Candide: or, Optimism (1947). It begins with a young man, Candide, who is living a sheltered life in an paradise and being indoctrinated with Leibnizian optimism (or simply Optimism) by his mentor, Pangloss. The work describes the abrupt cessation of this lifestyle, followed by Candide's slow, painful disillusionment as he witnesses and experiences great hardships in the world. Voltaire concludes with Candide, if not rejecting optimism outright, advocating a deeply practical precept, "we must cultivate our garden", in lieu of the Leibnizian mantra of Pangloss, "all is for the best in the best of all possible worlds". Candide is characterised by its sarcastic tone, as well as by its erratic, fantastical and fast-moving plot. A picaresque novel with a story similar to that of a more serious bildungsroman, it parodies many adventure and romance clich√©s, the struggles of which are caricatured in a tone that is mordantly matter-of-fact. Still, the events discussed are often based on historical happenings, such as the Seven Years' War and the 1755 Lisbon earthquake. As philosophers of Voltaire's day contended with the problem of evil, so too does Candide in this short novel, albeit more directly and humorously. Voltaire ridicules religion, theologians, governments, armies, philosophies, and philosophers through allegory; most conspicuously, he assaults Leibniz and his optimism. As expected by Voltaire, Candide has enjoyed both great success and great scandal. Immediately after its secretive publication, the book was widely banned because it contained religious blasphemy, political sedition and intellectual hostility hidden under a thin veil of na√Øvet√©. However, with its sharp wit and insightful portrayal of the human condition, the novel has since inspired many later authors and artists to mimic and adapt it. cleaned_message: Baths of the Seven Wise Men at Archaeological Park of Ancient Ostia. The Baths, built around 140 AD, take their name from the frescoes in one of the rooms depicting the "seven Greek sages" who lived around 600 BC. Their names and places of origin are written in ancient Greek next to the frescoes. Odd couples ü¶Ü Here I‚Äôve stumbled upon a mating pair of ducks that stick out like a sore thumb against a backdrop of common mallards! GOLDEN PLOVER (Pluvialis Apricaria) Conservation status: üü¢ As a ground nesting bird, Golden Plovers have to get really creative to keep their offspring safe from predators. As a result, their chicks produce a fluffy mottled green, white and brown plumage to help them blend in with various forms of moss and grass. The nests of moorland wading birds are particularly at risk of predation from Carrion Crows, Common Gulls and foxes. However, due to the stunning camouflaging of chicks along with the incredible speed at which the adult birds are capable of moving, numbers continue to bolster throughout the UK. Bonus fact: The Golden Plover is directly responsible for the existence of the Guinness World Records. The institution was set up in order to test and award the very first official World Record to the Golden Plover in order to settle an argument between avid sportsmen who were at odds over which species is the fastest game bird in Europe.

COMMON STARLING (Sturnus Vulgaris) Conservation status: üî¥ The stunning vocal range and mimicking capabilities of - that‚Äôs right - the common european starling! The likes of which just a few decades ago you would see common place across the entirety of the UK, but has dropped by over 66% since the 70s. Only 15% of juvenile starlings will make it to breeding age, at which point they face limited mating opportunities and habitats decimated by industrial agriculture and expanding urban zones. The primary cause of the starling decline? Starvation. Plain and simple. Starlings are one of the amazing bird species you are most likely to aid by setting up bird boxes and tables in your garden, allowing them a safe place to nest and graze. We have lost so much of our native wildlife, with just a small amount of effort, we could still save this one.

The Rotunda of St. George in Thessaloniki. The Rotunda, a symbol of Thessaloniki, was built in the first years of Roman tetrarchy, when Caesar Galerius (250-311 AD) was based in Thessaloniki. It was part of the imperial complex, probably in one theory built as Galerius‚Äô mausoleum, but was never used since his mausoleum was found in Romuliana, in Serbia. Not long after its construction, during the reign of the Byzantine Emperor Theodosios the Great (379-395 AD), the Rotunda was converted into a Christian church and a sanctuary was added on its eastern side. Between 1524 and 1591, the structure became Thessaloniki's cathedral and then, when the city fell to the Ottoman Turks, it was converted into a mosque until 1912, when it was dedicated to Saint George. @GreekLeague

Swan (Cygnus) A common but nonetheless elegant feature of our many waterways, the Swan is among one our largest birds here in the UK and is one of the most culturally significant creatures too. Both the Germanic (Swanaz) and Greco-Roman (cygnus/Œ∫œçŒ∫ŒΩŒøœÇ) etymologies for the Swan refer to the swan‚Äôs ‚Äòsinging‚Äô. Swans for the most part herbivorous, grazing on aquatic plants such as algae and submerged roots however they will also hunt and eat fish and amphibians, a task for which their serrated beaks are useful. Loyal companions, Swans mate for life and the male ‚Äòcob‚Äô assists the female ‚Äòpen‚Äô in her construction of the nest with both sharing the duty of nest-sitting. Swans elicit great sadness on the passing of their mate, ‚Äòsinging‚Äô mournfully. They are also fiercely protective of their young and have been known to drown humans who have interfered with their cygnets. Swans have a rich history in our lore and legend, originating from Aryan motifs regarding Divine Twins, often taking animal forms (Romulus & Remus/Hengist & Horsa) and have gone on to be the centre piece of much of our high culture, including Tchaikovsky‚Äôs Swan Lake and Wagner‚Äôs Lohengrin. Helen of Troy was said to be conceived by Zeus disguised as a Swan, Wayland the Smith married a swan maiden and of course the story of the Ugly Duckling is a childhood favourite. The Swans in the moat of Wells Cathedral‚Äôs Bishops Palace have for many centuries been trained to call for food by ringing bells by pulling at strings, something they still do to this day.

CROW, ROOK or RAVEN? These three large corvidae birds are extremely similar in their appearance, especially from afar, so here are a few ways to tell the difference. CROW ‚Ä¢ Smaller solid black beak with slight bill feathering ‚Ä¢ Tends to roam in large groups (murders) ‚Ä¢ Smooth plumage, particularly around head and throat ‚Ä¢ Tail feathers even in length, forming a fan shape ROOK ‚Ä¢ Large pale, straight beak with no feathering ‚Ä¢ Roams and lives in large rookeries ‚Ä¢ Long wings that narrow towards the body ‚Ä¢ Feathery trousers RAVEN ‚Ä¢ Large, rounded black beak with distinct bill feathers ‚Ä¢ Seen alone or with their mate only ‚Ä¢ Shaggy plumage around the head, throat and breast ‚Ä¢ Long, diamond shaped tail

Homemade Elderflower cordial. Ingredients: - 2.5kg Sugar. - 50g citric acid. - 40 elderflower heads, stalks trimmed. - 2 Lemons, unwaxed. - 1.5 litres water. You will also need two large pans, funnel, ladle, colender, bottles (swingtop, corked, etc) and a tea towel. - Sterilise all equipment. - Heat the water and sugar in a pan, taking care to not boil and stir occasionally. - Meanwhile, shake off the flower heads to remove any insects, debris. You can dip them in water to help dislodge any hangers on but preferable not to, if possible. - zest the Lemons and then slice, leave to the side. - Once the sugar has dissolved, bring to the boil and turn off the heat. - Add the other ingredients and gently stir. - Cover the pan and leave for 24 hours. - After 24 hours, line a colender with the tea towel and place over a clean pan. Pour in the liquid. - Transfer this filtered liquid to bottles. Should keep for 6 weeks or can be frozen in plastic. Mix with Soda water for a sparkling summers drink. Enjoy.

To achieve this, kestrels fly into the oncoming wind, matching its speed exactly - the particular feathering at the tips of the kestrels wings and tail are what makes it so uniquely equipped to hover for prolonged periods of time. Common British Kestrels, originally known as Old World Kestrels, are actually a small falcon species. While other types of falcons share the ability to hover for short periods, none are able to achieve what we see in this footage!

Ospreys have also been successfully reintroduced in central England at Rutland water. A White-tailed bumblebee helping pollinate my raspberries. My garden is filled full of flowers and herbs that are beneficial to pollinators. I have a cottage garden that is densely packed with various native species, or other beneficial cultivars, and a water source for birds and insects. In return for providing this habitat (aside from being able to enjoy the aesthetic of a cottage garden) i am rewarded with masses of beneficial insects that naturally keep pests, such as aphids, to a minimum and do a wonderful job pollinating my crops and subsequently giving me a higher yield. Gardening with wildlife in mind can be just as rewarding for your pantry as it is spiritually. Using flowers and herbs to help crop management was once a common practice and only really died out after the Victorian era. If you have some problems in the garden, try looking at more traditional methods before turning to chemicals.

May Day! What is it? May Day is an ancient pagan sacred day celebrating the beginning of Summer around May 1st. May Day is an important English tradition with rich festivities, and in the Celtic tradition was known as the Gaelic ‚ÄòBeltane‚Äô or ‚Äòfire of Bel‚Äô where the ancient Celts celebrated Summer with dancing & bonfires. The Green Man is the ultimate symbol of this tradition. Morris dancing is a form of ritual folk-dancing that is believed to have originated in the European courts of the 15th century. The Maypole dance is a ritual folk dance performed around a tall pole garlanded with greenery or flowers and often hung with ribbons that are woven into complex patterns by the dancers. Such dances are survivals of ancient dances around a living tree as part of spring rites to ensure fertility. Some British May Day traditions remark that girls would make a special point of washing their faces in the dew of the early morning to ensure they would be made beautiful in the year to come. https://t.me/britsloreuk/464

Eggs Benedict with a Hollandaise sauce. Ingredients: Breakfast Muffin Poached eggs Home cooked ham, sliced thinly. Salad leaves (gem lettuce is used here). For the sauce: 2 egg yolks 125g butter (and extra for the muffin) 1/2 teaspoon white wine vinegar Squeeze of lemon juice. Cayenne pepper (optional) Melt the butter in a small pan, seperating any solids that rise. In another pan, gently simmer some water and place a metal/glass bowl on top. Place the egg yolks, white wine vinegar, lemon juice, a splash of ice cold water and Cayenne pepper (if using) in the bowl and mix. Continually whisk the mixture to prevent scrambling. Once the sauce is thickened add the butter, mix, turn off the heat and keep warm (adding a splash of water if the sauce is too thick). Meanwhile, toast and butter the muffins and prepare your salad. Place your ham on the muffin and arrange the salad. Poach your eggs and place on top of your ham, pour over the sauce and season. Serve quickly. Pucka.

These are two of the most common bird species we encounter every day, and plenty of people don‚Äôt even realise they are actually two distinct breeds belonging to the dove family! ‚Ä¢ Wood Pigeons are the largest and most common dove in the UK, with a wingspan of 75-80cm vs the rock dove‚Äôs 65-70cm ‚Ä¢ Rock doves are easily recognisable for their iridescent purple/green neck, compared to the wood pigeons‚Äô green collar with notable white patch ‚Ä¢ Similarly, wood pigeon can be recognised by its reddish tinted breast and flash of white along the wing, whereas the rock doves‚Äô breast is typically grey along with double black band across the wings ‚Ä¢ While rock doves are often seen as pests in cities, these urban examples are actually a distinct mongrel breed known as ‚Äòferal pigeons‚Äô - descendants of released domestic birds. The only examples of pure breed wild rock doves to be found in the UK are on the cliffs of the far north/west coasts of Scotland
